## HubSpot Content Type Mapping

| GoodContent Type | HubSpot API Endpoint |
|---|---|
| Blog Post | /cms/v3/blogs/posts |
| Landing Page | /cms/v3/pages/landing-pages |
| Web Page | /cms/v3/pages/site-pages |
| Email | /marketing/v3/emails |
| Case Study / Guide | Blog Post with custom tag |

### HubSpot Draft Creation Contract (MVP Default)

Default publish flow is "create draft in HubSpot, review there, then publish from HubSpot UI."

Create payload fields to support in the HubSpot adapter:
- `contentGroupId` (required blog target)
- `name` (title)
- `postBody` (HTML)
- `metaDescription`
- `slug`
- `featuredImage`
- `blogAuthorId`
- `tagIds`
- `state: "DRAFT"` (default)

Auth model:
- Use HubSpot OAuth with content scopes for multi-tenant workspaces
- Do not rely on private app tokens for tenant-connected production flows

### HubSpot Operational Gotchas

- `postBody` must be clean semantic HTML to avoid template/module rendering issues
- `blogAuthorId` must exist in the target portal (onboarding should fetch/select or create author)
- `tagIds` should be resolved against existing portal tags (with optional create flow)
- Featured images should be uploaded to HubSpot File Manager or use a stable public URL

### Integration Expansion

HubSpot remains the deepest integration target for MVP and early GTM. Additional CMS connectors (for example WordPress) should be implemented behind a common publish adapter interface so core draft generation logic remains unchanged across destinations.

